83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
A-Engrossed
Senate Bill 1538
Ordered by the Senate February 11
Including Senate Amendments dated February 11
Printed pursuant to Senate Interim Rule 213.28 by order of the President of the Senate in conformance with pre-
session filing rules, indicating neither advocacy nor opposition on the part of the President (at the request
of Senate Interim Committee on Education)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability standards.
Digest: Tells schools how to respond to immigration issues. (Flesch Readability Score: 61.2).
Requires district school boards to admit all students to all schools and instructional programs
of the school district.
Prohibits discrimination in education related to immigration or citizenship status. Makes lim-
ited exceptions.
Adds requirements for model policies prepared by the Attorney General related to immigration
enforcement at public schools. Requires school districts and education service districts to [adopt
related policies and procedures and to provide training to district employees related to the policies and
procedures] provide applicable model policies to employees.
Takes effect July 1, 2026.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to conduct of public education; creating new provisions; amending ORS 180.810, 185.650,
3 332.405, 336.187, 339.115, 339.133, 340.005 and 659.850; and prescribing an effective date.
4 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
5
6 ACCESS TO SCHOOLS AND PROGRAMS
7
8 SECTION 1. ORS 339.115 is amended to read:
9 339.115. (1) Except as provided in ORS 339.141, authorizing tuition for courses not part of the
10 regular school program, the district school board shall admit free of charge to the schools and the
11 instructional programs of the district all persons between the ages of 5 and 19 who reside within
12 the school district. A person whose 19th birthday occurs during the school year shall continue to
13 be eligible for a free and appropriate public education for the remainder of the school year. A dis-
14 trict school board may admit nonresident persons, determine who is not a resident of the district
15 and fix rates of tuition for nonresidents.
16 (2)(a) A district must admit an otherwise eligible person who has not yet attained 21 years of
17 age prior to the beginning of the current school year if the person is:
18 (A) Receiving special education and has not yet received a high school diploma as described in
19 ORS 329.451; or
20 (B) Receiving special education and has received a modified diploma, an extended diploma or a
21 certificate of attendance as described in ORS 329.451.
22 (b) A district may admit an otherwise eligible person who is not receiving special education and
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 218

A-Eng. SB 1538
1 who has not yet attained 21 years of age prior to the beginning of the current school year if the
2 person is shown to be in need of additional education in order to receive a high school diploma or
3 a modified diploma.
4 (3) The obligation to make a free appropriate public education available to individuals with
5 disabilities 18 through 21 years of age who are incarcerated in an adult correctional facility applies
6 only to those individuals who, in their last educational placement prior to their incarceration in the
7 adult correctional facility:
8 (a) Were identified as being a child with a disability as defined in ORS 343.035; or
9 (b) Had an individualized education program as described in ORS 343.151.
10 (4) For purposes of subsection (3) of this section, “adult correctional facility” means:
11 (a) A local correctional facility as defined in ORS 169.005;
12 (b) A regional correctional facility as defined in ORS 169.620; or
13 (c) A Department of Corrections institution as defined in ORS 421.005.
14 (5) An otherwise eligible person under subsection (2) of this section whose 21st birthday occurs
15 during the school year shall continue to be eligible for a free appropriate public education for the
16 remainder of the school year.
17 (6) The person may apply to the board of directors of the school district of residence for ad-
18 mission after the 19th birthday as provided in subsection (1) of this section. A person aggrieved by
19 a decision of the local board may appeal to the State Board of Education. The decision of the state
20 board is final and not subject to appeal.
21 (7) Notwithstanding ORS 339.133 (2)(a), a school district shall not exclude from admission a child
22 located in the district solely because the child does not have a fixed place of residence or solely
23 because the child is not under the supervision of a parent, guardian or person in a parental re-
24 lationship.
25 (8) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, a school district:
26 (a) May for the remaining period of an expulsion deny admission to the regular school to a
27 resident student who is expelled from another school district; and
28 (b) Shall for at least one calendar year from the date of the expulsion and if the expulsion is for
29 more than one calendar year, may for the remaining period of time deny admission to the regular
30 school program to a student who is under expulsion from another school district for an offense that
31 constitutes a violation of a school district policy adopted pursuant to ORS 339.250 (7).
32 (9) Notwithstanding the minimum age requirement prescribed by ORS 339.010 and 339.020, a
33 district school board may admit free of charge a child whose needs for cognitive, social and physical
34 development would best be met in the school program, as defined by policies of the district school
35 board, to enter school even though the child has not attained the minimum age requirement but is
36 a resident of the district.
37
38 CLASSIFICATIONS OF PROHIBITED DISCRIMINATION
39
40 SECTION 2. ORS 659.850 is amended to read:
41 659.850. (1) As used in this section:
42 (a)(A) “Discrimination” means any act that unreasonably differentiates treatment, intended or
43 unintended, or any act that is fair in form but discriminatory in operation, either of which is based
44 on race, color, religion, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, national origin, immigration or
45 citizenship status, marital status, age or disability.
[2]

A-Eng. SB 1538
1 (B) “Discrimination” does not include enforcement of an otherwise valid dress code or policy,
2 as long as the code or policy:
3 (i) Provides, on a case-by-case basis, for reasonable accommodation of an individual based on the
4 health and safety needs of the individual; and
5 (ii) Does not have a disproportionate adverse impact on members of a protected class to a
6 greater extent than the policy impacts persons generally.
7 (C) “Discrimination” does not include:
8 (i) An act by a higher education program or service, school or interschool activity taken
9 for the purpose of complying with immigration or citizenship requirements that are:
10 (I) Imposed under federal law; or
11 (II) Required under the terms of a grant funded by a source that is not the higher edu-
12 cation program, service, school or activity; or
13 (ii) The charging of an international program fee by a higher education program or ser-
14 vice, school or interschool activity.
15 (b) “Race” includes physical characteristics that are historically associated with race, including
16 but not limited to natural hair, hair texture, hair type and protective hairstyles as defined in ORS
17 659A.001.
18 (2) A person may not be subjected to discrimination in any public elementary, secondary or
19 community college education program or service, school or interschool activity or in any higher
20 education program or service, school or interschool activity where the program, service, school or
21 activity is financed in whole or in part by moneys appropriated by the Legislative Assembly.
22 (3) The State Board of Education and the Higher Education Coordinating Commission shall es-
23 tablish rules necessary to ensure compliance with subsection (2) of this section in the manner re-
24 quired by ORS chapter 183.
25 SECTION 3. ORS 332.405 is amended to read:
26 332.405. (1) The district school board shall provide transportation for pupils or combinations of
27 pupils and other persons to and from school-related activities where required by law or when con-
28 sidered advisable by the board.
29 (2) The board may furnish board and room for pupils in lieu of transportation when reasonable
30 board and room can be provided at equal or less expense than transportation. The board may also
31 provide board and room in a facility that existed on July 1, 1998, or a replacement facility for that
32 facility, for pupils attending a district school as described in ORS 327.006 (6)(a)(B) or through a
33 power of attorney authorized under ORS 109.056 (2). Notwithstanding ORS 659.850, this subsection
34 does not apply to a pupil who attends a district school through a power of attorney and who is a
35 foreign exchange student enrolled in a school under a cultural exchange program.
36 (3) The transportation costs or expenses for board and room shall be paid from funds available
37 to the district for that purpose.
38 (4) The district school board may expend district funds to improve or provide for pedestrian fa-
39 cilities off district property if the board finds that the expenditure reduces transportation costs of
40 the district and enhances the safety of pupils going to and from schools of the district.
41 SECTION 4. ORS 339.133 is amended to read:
42 339.133. (1) As used in this section:
43 (a)(A) “Foster care” means substitute care for children placed by the Department of Human
44 Services or a tribal child welfare agency away from their parents and for whom the department or
45 agency has placement and care responsibility, including placements in foster family homes, foster
[3]

A-Eng. SB 1538
1 homes of relatives, group homes, emergency shelters, residential facilities, child care institutions and
2 preadoptive homes.
3 (B) “Foster care” does not mean care for children whose parent or guardian voluntarily placed
4 the child outside the child’s home with a public or private agency and for whom the child’s parent
5 or guardian retains legal guardianship.
6 (b)(A) “Person in parental relationship” means an adult who has physical custody of an indi-
7 vidual or resides in the same household as the individual, interacts with the individual daily, pro-
8 vides the individual with food, clothing, shelter and incidental necessaries and provides the
9 individual with necessary care, education and discipline.
10 (B) “Person in parental relationship” does not mean a person with a power of attorney or other
11 written delegation of parental responsibilities if the person does not have other evidence of a par-
12 ental relationship.
13 (c) “School district of origin” means the school district where an individual was a resident be-
14 fore:
15 (A) The individual was placed into foster care; or
16 (B) The foster care placement of the individual changed.
17 (d) “School of origin” means the school that an individual attended before:
18 (A) The individual was placed into foster care; or
19 (B) The foster care placement of the individual changed.
20 (2)(a) Except as provided in subsections (3) to (5) of this section, individuals between the ages
21 of 4 and 18 shall be considered resident for school purposes in the school district in which their
22 parents, their guardians or persons in parental relationship to them reside.
23 (b) Nonemancipated individuals between the ages of 4 and 18 living outside the geographic area
24 of the school district for such reasons as attending college, military service, hospital confinement
25 or employment away from home shall be considered resident in the district in which their parents,
26 their guardians or persons in parental relationship to them reside.
27 (c) Individuals living temporarily in a school district for the primary purpose of attending a
28 district school may not be considered resident in the district in which they are living temporarily,
29 but shall be considered resident in the district in which they, their parents, their guardians or per-
30 sons in parental relationship to them reside.
31 (3) Individuals considered legally emancipated from their parents shall be considered resident
32 in the district in which they actually reside, irrespective of the residence of their parents, their
33 guardians or persons in parental relationship.
34 (4)(a) An individual who is between the ages of 4 and 21 and who is placed in foster care shall
35 be considered a resident of:
36 (A) The school district of origin; or
37 (B) The school district where the individual resides due to placement by the Department of
38 Human Services or a tribal child welfare agency if a juvenile court determines it is not in the best
39 interest of the individual to continue attending the school of origin or any other school in the school
40 district of origin, based on consideration of all factors relating to the individual’s best interests.
41 (b) If a juvenile court makes a determination that it is not in the best interest of the individual
42 to continue attending the school of origin, the individual shall be immediately enrolled in a new
43 school, even if the individual is unable to produce records normally required for enrollment.
44 (c) Individuals who are residents of their school district of origin pursuant to paragraph (a)(A)
45 of this subsection shall:
[4]

A-Eng. SB 1538
1 (A) Remain in the individual’s school district of origin and, if applicable, the individual’s school
2 of origin for the duration of the individual’s time in foster care; and
3 (B) Be provided, free of charge, transportation between the individual’s home and the
4 individual’s school district of origin or, if applicable, the individual’s school of origin.
5 (d) The Department of Education, the Department of Human Services, tribal child welfare
6 agencies and school districts shall collaborate to ensure that the provisions of this subsection are
7 implemented.
8 (5)(a) Except as provided in ORS 327.006 (6) and 335.090, an individual whose legal residence is
9 not within the district but who attends school in the district is considered a resident in the district
10 in which the individual attends school if the individual receives written consent from both of the
11 affected district school boards as provided by policies adopted by the boards.
12 (b) An individual whose legal residence is not within the district but who attends school in the
13 district is considered a resident in the district in which the individual attends school if:
14 (A) The legal residence of the individual had been in the district in which the individual attends
15 school before a boundary change was made to the district;
16 (B) The legal residence of the individual is no longer in the district in which the individual at-
17 tends school because of the boundary change; and
18 (C) The individual has had the same legal residence and has continuously been enrolled in a
19 school in the district since the boundary change.
20 (6)(a) Notwithstanding ORS 659.850, individuals who are foreign exchange students and who
21 are residing in Oregon in a dormitory operated by a school district are considered to be residents
22 of the school district in which the dormitory is located.
23 (b) For the purpose of this subsection:
24 (A) An individual may not be considered to be a foreign exchange student for more than one
25 school year.
26 (B) An individual may be considered to be a resident of a school district as provided by this
27 subsection only if, for the 2010-2011 school year, the school district had foreign exchange students
28 who would have been considered residents under the provisions of this subsection.
29 (C) The number of individuals who may be considered residents under the provisions of this
30 subsection may not increase relative to the number who would have been considered residents under
31 the provisions of this subsection for the 2010-2011 school year.
32 (c) As used in this subsection, “foreign exchange student” means an individual who attends
33 school in Oregon under a cultural exchange program and whose parent, guardian or person in par-
34 ental relationship resides in another country.
35 SECTION 5. ORS 340.005 is amended to read:
36 340.005. For purposes of ORS 340.005 to 340.090:
37 (1) “Accelerated college credit program” has the meaning given that term by rules adopted by
38 the State Board of Education.
39 (2) “At-risk student” means:
40 (a) A student who qualifies for a free or reduced lunch program; or
41 (b) An at-risk student as defined by rules adopted by the board if the board has adopted rules
42 to define an at-risk student.
43 (3) “Duplicate course” means a course with a scope that is identical to the scope of another
44 course.
45 (4)(a) “Eligible post-secondary course” means any nonsectarian course or program offered
[5]

A-Eng. SB 1538
1 through an eligible post-secondary institution if the course or program may lead to high school
2 completion, a certificate, professional certification, associate degree or baccalaureate degree.
