4 resident school.
5 (c) “Eligible post-secondary course” includes:
6 (A) Academic courses;
7 (B) Career and technical education courses; and
8 (C) Distance education courses.
9 (5) “Eligible post-secondary institution” means:
10 (a) A community college;
11 (b) A public university listed in ORS 352.002; and
12 (c) The Oregon Health and Science University.
13 [(6)(a)] (6) “Eligible student” means a student who is enrolled in an Oregon public school and
14 who:
15 [(A)] (a) Is 16 years of age or older at the time of enrollment in a course under the Expanded
16 Options Program;
17 [(B)(i)] (b)(A) Is in grade 11 or 12 at the time of enrollment in a course under the Expanded
18 Options Program; or
19 [(ii)] (B) Is not in grade 11 or 12, because the student has not completed the required number
20 of credits, but who has been allowed by the school district to participate in the program;
21 [(C)] (c) Has developed an educational learning plan as described in ORS 340.025; [and]
22 [(D)] (d) Has not successfully completed the requirements for a high school diploma as estab-
23 lished by ORS 329.451, the State Board of Education and the school district board[.]; and
24 (e) Notwithstanding ORS 659.850, is not a foreign exchange student enrolled in a school
25 under a cultural exchange program.
26 [(b) “Eligible student” does not include a foreign exchange student enrolled in a school under a
27 cultural exchange program.]
28 (7) “Expanded Options Program” means the program created under ORS 340.005 to 340.090.
29 (8) “Scope” means depth and breadth of course content as evidenced through a planned course
30 statement including content outline, applicable state content standards where appropriate, course
31 goals and student outcomes.
32
33 MODEL POLICIES RELATED TO LAW ENFORCEMENT REQUESTS
34
35 SECTION 6. ORS 180.810 is amended to read:
36 180.810. (1) The Attorney General shall publish model policies intended to limit, to the fullest
37 extent possible consistent with state and federal law, immigration enforcement at public schools,
38 public health facilities, courthouses, public shelters and other public facilities operated by a public
39 body.
40 (2) For the purpose of developing a policy under subsection (1) of this section for public
41 schools for kindergarten through grade 12:
42 (a) The Attorney General shall consult with the Office of Immigrant and Refugee Ad-
43 vancement and with organizations representing school board members and other public
44 school professionals.
45 (b) In addition to any content of a policy developed under subsection (1) of this section,
[6]

A-Eng. SB 1538
1 a model policy published for public schools for kindergarten through grade 12 must include:
2 (A) A process for verifying the validity of any warrant or court order involving immi-
3 gration enforcement;
4 (B) A requirement that the superintendent of the school district or the education service
5 district, or the superintendent’s designee, review and approve any response to a law
6 enforcement request involving immigration enforcement;
7 (C) Provisions that encourage the superintendent of the school district or the education
8 service district, or the superintendent’s designee, to consult with legal counsel of the district
9 or a statewide or regional education organization prior to responding to any immigration
10 enforcement efforts;
11 (D) Requirements to ensure compliance with ORS 180.805 and 181A.826; and
12 (E) Recommendations for how employees of the school district, education service district
13 or public charter school will respond to immigration enforcement efforts.
14 (3)(a) All school districts, education service districts and public charter schools must
15 provide to the employees of the school district, education service district or public charter
16 school applicable model policies published by the Attorney General under this section.
17 [(2)] (b) All public bodies to which paragraph (a) of this subsection is not applicable are
18 encouraged to implement policies based on the model policies described in subsection (1) of this
19 section.
20 [(3)] (4) Any entity that contracts with a public body to provide services related to physical or
21 mental health, education or access to justice is encouraged to adopt policies based on the model
22 policies described in subsection (1) of this section.
23 [(4)] (5) The Attorney General may adopt rules to implement this section.
24 SECTION 7. ORS 185.650 is amended to read:
25 185.650. (1) There is established within the Department of Human Services the Office of Immi-
26 grant and Refugee Advancement for the purpose of operating a statewide immigrant and refugee
27 integration strategy.
28 (2) The Office of Immigrant and Refugee Advancement is under the supervision and control of
29 a director, who is responsible for the performance of the duties, functions and powers of the office.
30 The director shall be chosen through an open hiring process. In addition to the director, the office
31 shall include at least the following full-time staff members:
32 (a) One staff member who focuses on community partnerships;
33 (b) One staff member who focuses on data collection and research; and
34 (c) One staff member who focuses on administrative support for the office.
35 (3) The office shall:
36 (a) Advocate for and partner with statewide immigrant and refugee programs and services that
37 coordinate with long-term support services to meet the needs of immigrant and refugee populations
38 in this state;
39 (b) Collect data on immigrant and refugee populations in this state for the purposes of deter-
40 mining the needs of the populations and tracking progress in reducing social, economic and health
41 disparities for the populations;
42 (c) Monitor and protect data collected under this subsection and ensure that any data collected
43 and maintained by the office is not disclosed to any person or entity not affiliated with the office;
44 (d) Track state legislation that impacts immigrant and refugee populations in this state;
45 (e) Ensure that any racial and ethnic impact statements for legislation accurately include the
[7]

A-Eng. SB 1538
1 impact to immigrants and refugees in this state who are individuals who are Black, indigenous or
2 other people of color;
3 (f) Advocate for resources from the federal government to support the immigrant and refugee
4 populations;
5 (g) Monitor and, unless prohibited by federal or state law or rule, publish any investments made
6 by the state for the benefit and support of the immigrant and refugee populations;
7 (h) Partner with other state agencies as needed to meet the objectives of the office, including
8 the development of any model policies and procedures required by law;
9 (i) Partner with community-based organizations as needed to meet the objectives of the office;
10 and
11 (j) Adopt rules as necessary to carry out this section.
12 SECTION 8. ORS 336.187 is amended to read:
13 336.187. (1) As used in this section:
14 (a) “Health or safety emergency” includes law enforcement efforts to locate a child who
15 may be a victim of kidnap, abduction or custodial interference and law enforcement or child
16 protective services efforts to respond to a report of child abuse or neglect pursuant to ORS
17 419B.005 to 419B.050.
18 (b) “Law enforcement” does not include a federal immigration authority as that term is
19 defined in ORS 180.805.
20 [(1)] (2) A public school or school district shall disclose personally identifiable information or
21 other information allowed to be disclosed by the federal Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act
22 from an education record of a student to:
23 (a) Law enforcement, child protective services and health care professionals in connection with
24 a health or safety emergency if knowledge of the information is necessary to protect the health and
25 safety of the student or other individuals; and
26 (b) Courts and state and local juvenile justice agencies including[, but not limited to,] law
27 enforcement agencies, juvenile departments and child protective service agencies. Disclosure under
28 this paragraph must relate to the court’s or juvenile justice agency’s ability to serve the needs of
29 a student prior to the student’s adjudication under ORS chapter 419C. A person to whom personally
30 identifiable information is disclosed under this paragraph shall certify, in writing, that the person
31 will not disclose the information to a third party other than another court or juvenile justice agency
32 or a person or organization providing direct services to the student on behalf of a juvenile justice
33 agency.
34 [(2) As used in this section, a “health or safety emergency” includes, but is not limited to, law
35 enforcement efforts to locate a child who may be a victim of kidnap, abduction or custodial interference
36 and law enforcement or child protective services efforts to respond to a report of child abuse or neglect
37 pursuant to ORS 419B.005 to 419B.050.]
38 (3) A person who receives information under this section is not liable civilly or criminally for
39 failing to disclose the information.
